{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> λίσσομαι</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], Lyric poetry, Trag.; <i>Epic dialect</i> Iterat. λισσέσκετο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.451: \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist 1</i> ἐλῐσάμην, <i>Epic dialect</i> ἐλλ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.35; _imperative_ λίσαι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.394 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>subjunctive</i> <i>2nd pers.</i> <i>singular</i> λίσῃ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.526 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist 2</i> <i>infinitive</i> λῐτέσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.47; _optative_ λῐτοίμην 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.406 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]. (For <i>present</i> λίτομαι, see entry):—<b>beg, pray</b>, either <i>absolutely</i> or with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i>, λισσομένη προσέειπε Δία [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.502; εὐχωλῇσι λιτῇσί τε ἔθνεα νεκρῶν ἐλλισάμην 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.35, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; the thing by which one prays is found with ὑπέρ, λ. ὑπὲρ τοκέων, ὑπὲρ ψυχῆς καὶ γούνων, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.660, 22.338; λ. τινὰ ὑπὲρ πατρὸς καὶ μητέρος 24.467 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: or simply in <i>genitive</i>, λ. Ζηνὸς ἠδὲ Θέμιστος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.68; λ. τινὰ γούνων 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.451, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 22.337 (for which in 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.45 we have λαβὼν ἐλλίσσετο γούνων,compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.142; τῆ ἑτέρῃ μὲν ἑλὼν ἐλλίσσετο γούνων 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.71; ἥπτετο χείρεσι γούνων ἱέμενος λίσσεσθ᾽ 20.469)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also in Trag., πρὸ.. τέκνων σε λ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Troades” 1045 (see. below): an \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i> is frequently added, as οὐδέ σ᾽ ἔγωγε λίσσομαι εἵνεκ᾽ ἐμεῖο μένειν I do not <b>pray</b> thee to remain, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.174, compare 283, 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 10.69, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.207; πρός νυν θεῶν σε λ. ἐμοὶ πιθέσθαι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 428 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; καὶ μὴ προδοῦναι λ. <b>prays</b> her not to abandon him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 202: more rarely with an _accusative_ and \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i> added, λίσσονται Δία.. Ἄτην ἅμ᾽ ἕπεσθαι they <b>pray</b> Zeus <b>that</b> Ate may follow, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.511, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.30: sometimes followed by ὅπως, λίσσεσθαί μιν, ὅπως νημερτέα εἴπῃ\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <b>entreat</b> him to say the truth, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3.19 \">Refs</a>]; or by ἵνα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 327: in Trag. parenthesis, μὴ πρόλειπε, λ., πάτερ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 748; μή, λίσσομαί σ᾽, αὔδα τάδε 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 368, compare “OT” 650 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 382. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>beg</b> or <b>pray for</b>, οἷ αὐτῷ θάνατον καὶ κῆρα λιτέσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.47:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] with <i>double</i> <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i> et _of things_, ταῦτα μὲν οὐχ ὑμέας ἔτι λίσσομαι this <b>I beg</b> of you no more, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.210, compare 4.347. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus frequently with _dative_ modi, ἐπέεσσι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.98, +others; εὐχῇσι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.526; εὐχωλῆσι λιτῆσί τε ἐλλισάμην 11.35.—Rare in Prose, as 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.24, LXX.Job.17.2, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Syr.D.” 18; in 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 366a there is a reference to 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.501 \">LXX+8th c.BC+</a>]. [The λ- frequently makes position in <i>Epic dialect</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.394, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; written λλ after the augment, see above]","strongNumber":"G8204","accentedUnicode":"λίσσομαι","shortDef":"to implore","mediumDef":"to implore","stepGloss":"to implore","stepTransliteration":"lissomai","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}